definition.value: An O-acylcarnitine having icosanoyl (arachidoyl) as the acyl substituent.
An O-acylcarnitine having 3-hydroxyarachidonoyl as the acyl substituent.
An O-acylcarnitine having (9Z)-17-carboxyheptadec-9-enoyl as the acyl substituent.
An O-acylcarnitine having 3-hydroxyeicosanoyl as the acyl substituent.
An O-acylcarnitine having 17-carboxyheptadecanoyl as the acyl substituent.
An O-acylcarnitine having behenoyl (docosanoyl) as the acyl substituent.
An O-acylcarnitine having (9Z)-3-hydroxydodecenoyl as the acyl substituent.
A pentacyclic triterpenoid isolated from Maprounea africana and has been shown to exhibit inhibitory activity against HIV-1 reverse transcriptase.
An O-(hydroxytetradecadienoyl)carnitine having (5Z,8Z)-3-hydroxytetradecadienoyl as the acyl substituent.
An O-(hydroxyhexadecadienoyl)carnitine having (9Z,12Z)-3-hydroxyhexadecadienoyl as the acyl substituent.
A carbohydrate acid derivative anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group of GM1 ganglioside.
A hydrate that is the monohydrate form of anhydrous esculin.
An alkane-alpha,omega-diamine in which the two amino groups are separated by eight methylene groups.
A carboxylic ester obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of divinyl chlorophyll a with the hydroxy group of (2E,7R,11R)-3,7,11,15-tetramethylhexadec-2-en-1-ol.
A carboxylic ester obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of divinyl chlorophyll b with the hydroxy group of (2E,7R,11R)-3,7,11,15-tetramethylhexadec-2-en-1-ol.
An O-acylcarnitine having (9Z,12Z,15Z)-3-hydroxyoctadecatrienoyl as the acyl substituent.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine in which the 1- and 2-acyl groups are specified as hexadecanoyl (palmitoyl) and 5Z,8Z,11Z,14Z-eicosatetraenoyl (arachidonoyl) respectively.
An O-acylcarnitine having (11Z)-eicoseneoyl as the acyl substituent.
An O-acylcarnitine having (11Z,14Z)-eicosadienoyl as the acyl substituent.
An O-acylcarnitine having (13Z,16Z)-docosadienoyl as the acyl substituent.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine in which the 1- and 2-acyl groups are specified as hexadecanoyl (palmitoyl) and 9Z,12Z-octadecadienoyl (linoleoyl) respectively.
An O-acylcarnitine having (7Z,10Z,13Z,16Z)-docosatetraenoyl as the acyl substituent.
An O-acylcarnitine having (7Z,10Z,13Z,16Z,19Z)-docosapentaenoyl as the acyl substituent.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine in which the 1- and 2-acyl groups are specified as hexadecanoyl (palmitoyl) and 9Z-octadecenoyl (oleoyl) respectively.
An organophosphate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of 2,3-bis-O-phytanyl-sn-glycerol 1-phosphate; major species at pH 7.3.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine in which the 1- and 2-acyl groups are specified as hexadecanoyl (palmitoyl) and octadecanoyl (stearoyl) respectively.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine in which the 1- and 2-acyl groups are both specified as hexadecanoyl (palmitoyl).
An abietane diterpenoid that is abieta-8,12-diene substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 7 and 12 and oxo groups at positions 11 and 14 (the 7alpha stereoisomer) .
A thiochromane that is acetylene in which the hydrogens are replaced by 5-carboxypyridin-2-yl and 4,4-dimethylthiochroman-6-yl groups. It is the active form of the prodrug tazarotene.
An aromatic amino acid that is nicotinic acid in which one of the hydrogens attached to the pyridine ring is replaced by an amino group. A 'closed class'.
A glycerophospholipid that is sn-glycerol 1-phosphate carrying two O-phytanyl groups at positions 2 and 3.
The (6aS,11aS)-enantiomer of pterocarpan.
The (6aR,11aR)-enantiomer of pterocarpan.
A 1-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine in which the 1-acyl group is specified as hexadecanoyl (palmitoyl).
A ceramide 1-phosphate that is the N-hexacosanoyl derivative of sphingosine.
An EC 1.1.1.* (oxidoreductase acting on donor CH-OH group, NAD(+) or NADP(+) acceptor) inhibitor that interferes with the action of carbonyl reductase (NADPH), EC 1.1.1.184.
A ceramide 1-phosphate that is N-tetracosanoyl derivative of sphingosine.
A ceramide 1-phosphate that is the N-docosanoyl derivative of sphingosine.

A cyclohexenecarboxylic acid that is cyclohex-1-ene-1-carboxylic acid which is substituted at positions 3, 4, and 5 by pentan-3-yloxy, acetamido, and amino groups, respectively (the 3R,4R,5S enantiomer). An antiviral drug, it is used as the corresponding ethyl ester prodrug, oseltamivir, to slow the spread of influenza.
A ceramide 1-phosphate that is the N-icosanoyl derivative of sphingosine.
A purine nucleoside in which guanine is attached to arabinofuranose via a beta-N(9)-glycosidic bond. It inhibits DNA synthesis and causes cell death.
An optically active form of 4-hydroxy-2-oxohexanoate having 4S-configuration.
An optically active form of 4-hydroxy-2-oxopentanoate having 4S-configuration.
A ceramide 1-phosphate that is the N-octadecananoyl (stearoyl) derivative of sphingosine.
A ceramide 1-phosphate that is the N-hexadecanoyl (palmitoyl) derivative of sphingosine.
A ceramide 1-phosphate that is N-tetradecanoyl (myristoyl) derivative of sphingosine.
A ceramide 1-phosphate that is the N-decanoyl derivative of sphingosine.
An optically active form of 4-hydroxy-2-oxopentanoic acid having 4S-configuration.
An optically active form of 4-hydroxy-2-oxohexanoic acid having 4S-configuration.
